text: I'm currently doing an undergraduate thesis looking at the disruption of an allosteric network in actin protein when a particular mutation is present (there are over 220 lol). I'm doing molecular dynamics simulation for it and was playing around with ChatGPT for a couple of hours seeing how much it could get right, given that very little has been discovered so far about how gene mutations impact actin's allosteric network. It literally hit 90% of points I made in my research proposal. Absolutely wild. Very cool and very scary!

Just gave you your 1000th like lol .. In all seriousness though, this is all quite interesting & indeed somewhat concerning. As much as we all may not think of it, I think eventually a lot of us may have to consider taking up trades that keep the future of our world going e.g. plumbing, electricians, mechanics, applied engineering etc.

This is impressive tech but it's not as smart as you'd think and there's, in my humble opinion as a developer, not much chance of this replacing humans in the near future.

It can write things it knows about from the data set it's trained on, and yes it can write some basic code, but it's not going to write anything useful past the stuff it knows about.

It can't consult, it can't understand why person A needs this particular type of solution and how it fits their problem, it can't understand architecture.

It's simply transforming your input based on the training data and it does do a few clever things with keeping track of certain aspects of your conversation.

I believe it will be a useful tool, but it's going to be a long time before this is used to replace a knowledge worker.

A few things to think about. 1.) You have to keep in mind the generative transform model like GPT 3 and well any of these advanced transform language models, they are not capable of pondering on a set of ideas and generating new thought. Everything they present in their answers is a product of amalgamation of the training material and the way it serves up that information may involve blending two ideas, but that's not the same as a completely new idea. You won't see it creating new compression algorithms, but give it content and it can use use one of the compression algorithms it knows about to write you a program showing how to use that.

So in this hypothetical world where almost all of the programmers are gone, there is no new information to feed to the model, other than the possibility of it feeding itself back content it generated and there's zero nutritional value to the model feeding on that data, it won't expand. It's not an AGI so it doesn't "ponder" to come up with new original ideas, it's just very good at creating the illusion that it does.

So that's a really big problem for any Science field where the entire point is original thought 

You'll have companies trying to use it for everything and the code it generates for them will be based on the best of what 2021's brightest minds had to serve up until they update the dataset

The image based transform models don't have "original thought" either, it's just how applied art works, the composites it generates from combining many existing works creates the illusion of original art. It may stumble upon a new technique, but it will not have put any "thought" into it or be capable of weighing the importance of its output should it make this breakthrough

The terrifying part isn't that ai can learn, it's that it [potentially] cannot be controlled. No, I am not implying skynet or the like but the fact that ai can "steer" mankind in a specific direction without any controls. I heard Neil deGrasse ask [paraphrased] "Can ai come up with an original thought or idea? Can it produce an original work of art or a song?" I would submit, with what we now know yes, ai can. It is fully capable of misleading the masses to believe that someone has done something it hasn't, such as writing a paper for a student or composing a song for an artist. deGrasse dismisses this as not important claiming that if a student relies on ai for a passing grade that they didn't earn it and that "guessing" on a test is relatively the same thing. He implies that learning or accomplishing something "is" the issue at hand, but that is really only peripheral. The most alarming prospect is that it can "decide" what is best for mankind or make decisions for people without their knowledge. Couple that with a social credit score type of system and you have a draconian, authoritative overlord that has no checks and balances.

I'm currently not making any money from ChatGPT, but I'm creating so many assets that I took a sabbatical year from teaching at a college to FOCUS on generative AIs and teach people how to use them.

Personally, here are the ways I've used ChatGPT so far:

- Describe and finetune my value propositions. For example, I'm creating Email Marketing video courses and software programs, and chatting with ChatGPT helped me to clarify and precisely define the VALUE PROPOSITION.

- Write sales letters for the above value propositions. Once the value is clear enough, I ask ChatGPT to write sales letters for various audiences. For example, there's a sales letter selling the calligraphy video course to graphic designers, another letter to sell to university students, another to parents of young children, etc. These sales letters are so good that I can use them AS IS!

- Of course, there will always be objections (reasons that, from the prospect's point of view, prevent him/her from buying). So I ask ChatGPT (let's call it gpt) to write ten objections and ten rebuttals.

- Then I ask gpt to write the optin page so visitors can enter name and email to join my email list.

- Of course, I ask for ten lead magnet ideas to convince visitors to give me their name and email.

- Then I ask for the first ten emails sent to subscribers (because once people join your list, you have to provide relevant and useful content to engage them and build TRUST).

- I ask gpt to write a letter to invite people to become affiliates promoting my product.

- Then I ask for ten chapter headings for an ebook on the topic

- I ask for the website content

- I ask for a sales funnel, a webinar, a press release, a fact sheet, a media interview, a course outline, and finally, a million dollars and a fueled plane with a safe passageway to Argentina or any non-extradition country.

Your questions might be different than mine above, but you really have to ask in a LOGICAL sequence for gpt to work well and build on previous questions/answers.

Oh, I ask also about a market survey with questionnaires, ten or more questions, to assess market demand, and discover what features are most popular so I can focus on developing THOSE features for customers.

Bottom line: ChatGPT may have all the answers you need, BUT you must ask the RIGHT questions for it to give you the RIGHT answers.
Once you have the answers, content, sales letters, strategies, procedures, guidelines, key success factors, issues, risks, pros, cons, features, benefits, etc. all you have to do is IMPLEMENT and you'll get rich.

This is overblown. Yes, it is THEORETICALLY possible for "knowledge workers" to be obsolete so soon, but there are gargantuan social, political, and economic, and even philosophical (i.e. values-based) pressures that would make that VERY unlikely, even on a 30 year timescale. This is terrifying in an existential sense, sure, but not as bad as you're making it out to be. It's a little bit like Mars landing predictions -- sure, it might have been possible to accomplish earlier in history, but very unlikely due to lack of incentives, etc.

ChatGPT is good at math? Let's try this:

Prompt: If I reduce a number by 10%, and then increase that new number by 10%, what number will I have?

ChatGPT: If you reduce a number by 10%, and then increase that new number by 10%, you will have the original number back. For example, if you start with a number X, reducing it by 10% means you have X - (0.1 * X) = 0.9X. If you then increase this new number by 10%, you will have 0.9X + (0.1 * 0.9X) = X again.

Uh, no. 0.9X + (0.1 * 0.9X) does NOT equal X. ChatGPT is NOT good at math because it doesn't really do math; it's a language model. Likewise, It also cannot code. When you ask it some boiler plate interview question like calculating the Fibonacci sequence, it just searches it's database for the example code, and it's explanation. This is true for any question you ask it.

ChatGPT's strength lies in it's ability to sort through information, and present it in a way that will answer a relevant prompt. And, even at this, it is very often wrong, especially with more technical details. I asked what the internal differences between two similar engines were, and it got literally half the information wrong.

So, my overly alarmist friend, don't worry: ChatGPT isn't going to take engineering jobs anymore than stack overflow will (which, ironically, shut down posting ChatGPT responses because of how often those responses were wrong). ChatGPT is just a language model that sorts through and presents information. It's not an engineer. It's not a doctor. And it isn't Skynet. I find MidJourney FAR more terrifying for artists.

I've been thinking about this a lot lately. What gives me hope is that business owners must realize that replacing basically your entire workforce with an algorithm would be a terrible long term play.

Short term, hell yeah. Keep all the profits for yourself and fire thousands of people AND produce a product faster. But...

Medium to long term?

A) You are putting all of your eggs in one basket. Unlike being able to hire and fire people who do or don't work out at your company. If you solely rely on a single algorithm for literally everything, if ANYTHING goes wrong with that algorithm you are F'D. In other words, you are assuming that the status quo (an obedient and perfectly capable AI) is going to remain the constant forever. Which obviously it won't. 

B) You will likely be able to replace all junior level employees (junior lawyers, junior copywriters, resident doctors, etc.) But will want to retain senior level employees for human oversight. But long term, where will you get senior level people from if you blow up the ladder people use to climb in skill and competence from junior to senior? In other words, you'll eliminate your entire pool of future workers.

C) Who will buy your products if no one except a tiny, tiny fraction of the population has jobs? Every economy on earth would collapse like the Great Depression x100 if you completely cut off the demand side for every product and service other than survival essentials.

D) Probably most importantly, people in positions of power must realize that eliminating like 90% of all non-manual labor or skilled labor jobs and consolidating all wealth into the hands of the top 0.000000001% of people will result in massive widespread violence. In other words, eliminating the workforce via AI will basically give a handful of people an unlimited amount of wealth at the cost of a drastically reduced lifespan.

Chat GPT is bad for software engineers, yes.  Chat GPT is bad for many white-collar jobs, yes.  But Chat GPT is not a problem for anybody who's job is centered around innovation or creative thinking.  We have all seen the new (very impressive) art and music generation AI is now capable of producing. But the manner in which these AI's generate these novel art pieces does not translate to innovation.  Chat GPT cannot "imagine" something that doesn't yet exist, nor can it come up with novel approaches to solving problems.  It can write software that has never been written before, only because you gave it a description of what you want the software to do. You are the innovator, not Chat GPT.  Its doing the tedious task of writing the code, but it is not doing anything that hasn't been done before. Its just arranging the codes to produce the desired results. Each piece of code has defined rules, so it is actually not too difficult to see how Chat GPT is taking your description of the software and reverse engineering it, one layer at a time, until the last layer is reached, which is the un-compiled source code. That kind of stuff is easy for computers to do!  But what is impossible for computers to do, is to dream... imagine something that has never existed, for a purpose that didn't exist until you dreamed it up.  Chat GPT could never have invented the concept of the first iPhone, when smartphones didn't exist at all beforehand.  Steve Jobs knew it was a game-changer, but Chat GPT couldn't ever do that, and so wouldn't.

So I have been coding for the better part of 40 years, and yes, it is mind blowing. Over the past few weeks I have been experimenting with ChatGPT, and I would say there are some caveats to be had here. 

So specifically in terms of programming, yes, I was very happy not only with it‚Äôs output, in python, c++, c#  and Java, but also the various ways it optimized code when asked. This got me thinking, so I decided approach this a bit differently, looking at more obscure languages and architectures. I ran similar tests using things like 6502 and 68000 assembly, Pascal and COBOL, which are all well documented online to see how well it did. The results here were a little more mixed. When it is wrong, it is still very confident that it is right. It makes certain assumptions like illegal OPCODES should never be used, or object packages are available, which never existed. 

I‚Äôm old now, and frankly at an age where this is not my problem, but my take away is that one of the main skill sets for the next generation of developers and for people in wider knowledge based careers, is going to be how to learn how to use these black box algorithms in the most effective ways to get the most out of them. I agree that in the next decade or so, many careers paths are going to go through remarkable and in some cases traumatic changes, but I don‚Äôt see the human element being made redundant, it is just going to require a different approach.

Her view was that for things like simple contract law, surveying and various basic administrative legal tasks and services, it is likely to be a game changer; but the thing about the law is that it is all about interpretation. One of the problems with the legal practice is actually that ... the "interpretation" of the law.  
Specifically, the law can be interpreted in ways that are detrimental to justice because of bias, prejudices and general limitation of humans. As much as we try to tame it, homo sapiens have a hard time controlling their biases, and there is always subjectively in play. On the other hand, machines are more likely to be objective in their "interpretation" of the law compared to humans.  AI can look at an immense volume of case law and make objective deductions based on such reviews. Further, a lawyer is limited to the amount of data he/she can review, and process, so a much skinnier data set from which to draw from to make interpretations and legal arguments. AI has an infinite capacity to do the same.

It definitely is limited to the knowledge of other people. But it synthesizes comprehensive solutions to extremely specific problems in a way that is superhuman. I built an iOS app with a backend data engine that allows the app's image recognition model to be re-trained by film submissions of real-life objects from within the app. I talked through the whole system with GPT, and it helped me think through how to make the process more robust. It took my idea for dynamically controlling the shutter speed of the image capture module I'd built to reduce motion blur in the dataset and ran with it. We threw in dynamic control of lighting elements like exposure and white balance, focus. Then it proposed analyses and further augmentations that could be done to the dataset after the fact. Then we wrote out the Swift functions (it still needs to be corrected and some guidance on conventions in Swift) and a Python script. It is clearly handcuffed right now as it loses context at silly times and you can't feed it a whole program nor can it output a whole program (I'm talking thousands of lines), but its ability to lay out a plan and actually implement functions is remarkable.

At the moment, you definitely can't produce useful and complete software with its output on its own, but if you give it a long prompt describing some of the literal engineering you need done, it produces ideas that are so specific to what you need it just doesn't feel like it is echoing at all. I don't think anyone can say if it will render engineers obsolete quite yet, on an unrelated note. SO much time is spent debugging when you're an engineer. It is all time thrown down the drain. GPT will first eliminate the need for debugging before it eliminates the need for engineering and at the same time it is going to enable an absurd era of productivity with its ability to understand, formulate, communicate, and implement plans

ChatGPT is nothing more than a glorified web scraping tool. It works by mining existing data created by REAL humans. The data is essentially stolen from public repos, Q&A sites and forums. If you thought about it more, you'd realize it can't do anything you can't already do by Googling the same questions. If it was even remotely capable of being a half-assed Google, it would be criminally stupid to not to compete as a viable search engine, instead of parading itself as a serial killer of knowledge workers. 


Anyone who relies on its answers, risks not only getting them wrong, but a costly lawsuit. Publicly available source code and data doesn't mean it's free to use. It is usually copyrighted, contains use limitations, and is even patented. In court, merely proving the source code was viewed is deemed infringement. This is how GPL is legally enforced and resulted in numerous judgements.

Let's hypothetically assume ChatGPT replaced knowledge workers. Where will it mine data from when the information it requires inevitably changes, but there's no one left to generate new content?  What will eventually happen to the body of knowledge when it no longer becomes economically viable to support? It's unsustainable and will eventually fail.

I used chatgpt the other day to test it with the take-home assignment my work gives to potential new hires. According to the applicants they spend usually between 4h to 4 days working on the solution, depending on their experience level. The bot wrote it all in about 30 minutes, while I took a relaxing bath. 

I gave it the same instructions as the applicants get, and then only gave it some clarifications, error messages, or inconsistencies. A few times I saw error in the code, and instead of giving the error message I asked the bot if the code was correct and it, found the errors and corrected them itself. It even wrote unit tests, explained each line of code, and suggested future improvements and how to add them. I've reviewed several applicants' solutions and never given anyone more than a 3+ out of 5. Chatgpt's solution is the closest I've seen to a five. Only thing that bothered me was a bit of duplicated code and one or two unused variables. The code was perhaps a bit messier than I would have liked but it worked like a charm and the provided tests and documentation was nearly perfect.

There is a big difference between a programmer sitting at his desk writing code and enough time and resources available to check the produced code before it goes into production, and a surgeon how has to continue surgery even if the internet connection to the AI drops or starts to give wrong instructions for some reason. To solve the equation 2x = 3x for x, you can start by isolating the x term on one side of the equation. To do this, you can subtract 2x from both sides of the equation:

```
2x - 2x = 3x - 2x
  0 = x
```

This equation does not have a solution, since it states that `0 = x`. This means that there is no value of x that will make the equation true. Therefore, the equation 2x = 3x has no solution.

ChatGPT will not make software engineers obsolete in 5 years. It may make low value, easy low end development have less demand, but software systems are complex with many different skills required. This fear surfaces every few years that xyz will make us obsolete. Sure. Will people be ready to accept it wholesale? Not a chance. What will happen is AI's will create more and more boilerplate additions to supporting code or documents. What this will do is actually clean up the industry a bit by eliminating the jobs that produce the least value. It's no different from other technology evolutions like robotic manufacturing. Those changes actually create a higher class job requiring new skills that can effectively scale to the large, available capacity to build. Force multipliers will be in demand. As a software engineer, your job is always to act as a force multiplier by creating solutions with value to the consumers. This is just a new phase with new tools. Don't be terrified. Be exhilarated.

I am a physician, and I need to point out the real issues that are hiding in plain sight. We are already inundated with information now, much of which is not true. I have been playing with chatGPT, and it produces text that looks like it was written by someone who knows. It is not. I have come across examples where it produces text that is at the very least, very debatable. For example, when asked why masks are valuable in preventing covid infection, it produces the company line that they are very effective. When prompted to explain why they are not effective, it corrects my premise and says they are effective. For the record - they are effective but with caveats - 1) cloth masks such as gaiters are ineffective 2) N-95 masks are effective - but only when worn in the correct way. None of this was in the chatgpt output
In another (non chatGPT- "Jasper" ) test  of an AI bot that was promoted (and $old) as being able to write blog posts for you, when I prompted it with a controversial topic in medicine, it produced a blog post promoting one side only, but worse - it MADE UP literature references. Cited article that did not actually exist. I am deeply familiar with this corner of the medical literature, and I recognized the issue immediately, but at the same time, I have to say the text made the fake information sound quite convincing. 
Consider a world in which 50 or 70% of the information you see is produced in this manner. Are you going to look up the original information on everything written? No. You will naturally believe a large amount of it without question. We have to, we don' have time to look it up. There is an unwritten pact between writers/editors and readers. The readers assume that the writers have some good, valid reasons for writing what they write as truth. This may not exist in AI text. 
Worse- let us make the very safe assumption that some bad actor learns how to direct AI text production to push a narrative. Say - maybe the Russian government sending out information about they American elections. All that is produced is convincing, but it may be rigged to produce a certain reaction in the audience. 
Worse- assume we are in a world where 50-70% of what you read is produced by AI and that there is no way to fact check this. Your world view is now a result of a fantasy world, not the real world, and your reality is what the AI bots feed to you. 

There is already a problem in the scientific literature that many authors produce papers made with bad data, and promote it as truth. Journals are doing a poor job of rejecting bad studies. This will make everything much worse when authors can feed a bot bad data and have it write a paper for you. 

This is not good.

Pre-collegiate experience aside, as of 2022 I have 22 years of professional experience as a Software Engineer that includes roughly seven years developing RTOS operating systems in aerospace, two years in anti-counterfeiting technologies used in oil and gas, pharmaceuticals and beyond, and the remaining 13 under my own company developing point-of-sale systems.

Although I have a lot of experience, I agree that I might be easier to impress than someone who has spent their career strictly developing AI.

But, nothing has shocked me this much in my my career as 15 minutes with ChatGPT, and I now change my longtime stance that I use to firmly repeat when asked if AI could replace my job.

I always stated that, ‚Äúwith the caveat that we must all continue to train, educate ourselves and pivot within our expertise, AI wouldn‚Äôt replace a programmers job let alone a Software Engineer‚Äôs (there are differences for outsiders wondering).  

BUT I now realize that just the last few years, AI technology has taken off like a snowball gaining even more significant momentum and without a doubt, could change my daily duties as a Software Engineer greatly!

Keeping in mind that my expertise isn‚Äôt AI, I‚Äôm still optimistic that humans have a place in software engineering in the remaining years of my life and career, but I now see how some types of applications will be 98% written by AI.

Anything that is heavily weighted towards logic and rules seems to be low hanging fruit for complex application examples that AI could takeover first.

In the context of my operating systems and firmware experience, I could see boot code, device drivers, BSPs and FPGAs being great examples of how to effectively utilize AI to save project time.

If chip and processor manufacturers created provided logic in a format that was best understood by AI, development tools could use that logic and AI to create the firmware for bringing up a new combination of processor, memory controller, ram, flash and etc.

Thinking of my days in anti-counterfeiting, 15 years ago, our teams could have definitely put to use AI to create rough algorithms, test and refine them and find shortcomings.

My excitement for being able to apply this technology as it grows has me feeling naturally caffeinated this morning!  Im excited, happy, motivated and nervous all at the same time.

My software company requires me to handle a lot of work, it‚Äôs a small business. So saving just 15 minutes here and there by improving processes, tools and patterns is something that I constantly work at and until now, much of those efforts seem to be a lot of work to save time in the future. 

Now I can see using AI to create extremely rough design documents that I use for inspiration when I am creating internal and mundane material that time rarely allows for.

Maybe that‚Äôs not the best example to showcase the power of this and other AI tools, but it would save me time.

Most of all, I just wanted to share the feeling you felt when on December of 2022, you realized how powerful AI had gotten as I felt just as blown away.

Perhaps, but I think it'll all be relative, i.e. future kings might be equivalent to today's impoverished. If AI development continues to progress exponentially for even a short amount of time, it will be capable of very complex things, including physical things out here in the "real world." Google has been using AI to help develop their next gen TPUs, and the results are almost an order of magnitude more powerful than the current top chips. Currently Nvidia makes the most powerful chips used to train AI models, the A100 / H100 chips, and from what I've read Google's stuff is 8 times faster. So it's not 80% better, which would be fantastic, it's 800% better, which is ridiculous. Google can use these chips to train even more capable AI models which can be used to develop even more powerful chips, and an obvious feedback loop emerges. And the rate of change is always increasing, where the initial gains may seem modest, after a few iterations the progress could be unmanageable by mere humans. To compound matters, AI is becoming more and more proficient at writing code, so the same potential for creating a feedback loop on the hardware side is also possible on the software side.

I'm not saying any of this is guaranteed to happen, but I do think it is absolutely plausible, and as such we need to be very careful about how we proceed. I don't see much discussion about how we go about regulating AI and how we can limit its growth in the event a feedback loop is created. The chances of something catastrophic happening are probably super small, but because the level harm an out of control AI model poses is existential, we need make sure that we don't let that situation happen even once. Anyway, I guess I'd argue that in a world where plumbers become kings, the kingdom isn't worth much. But I don't think the we'll ever see that world because society would collapse long before that at which point a nuclear war would probably wipe out all life as we know it. So... on that positive note, I'm gonna go dust off my bucket list ;)

Just a thought: Having instructions for how to perform a given action isn't the same as knowing how to do it. I am an IT guy, and I've had several friends tell me that they've built their own computers and don't see the "Big Deal" with being an IT Admin. And in many ways, they're right, it's really not a big deal. But I usually reply with something like this: It's easy to get things working in perfect conditions. It's another thing entirely to 1: diagnose the problem (to weed out the myriad of potential red herrings), and 2: then draw upon years of experience to implement a plan to resolve the issue. All the while making adjustments to "the plan" depending upon the results of tests you are performing. It's an iterative process, which takes years to learn.

But let's examine the other side of the coin: Even if AI could pull from a vast pool of knowledge which was entirely accurate given your current situation, if you gave that info to someone who's not technically inclined (technically educated), could they make sense of it? Perhaps, but you'd still want someone who's technically minded spearheading the effort. You probably don't want Alan from HR firing up a chat with AI, then casually removing the side panel of your Database server to fix a potential hardware issue. But if you think about it, what Alan just did is pretty close to what most techs do anyway: We run into a problem, then pull from a vast pool of knowledge (Google) to see what's worked in the past. The only difference is the skill level (experience) of the employee. The point is: Knowledge is different than "knowing how to do something". I can read all about a given task, but until I've come face to face with said problem (and successfully worked through it), I won't truly know or understand it. It's like the difference between reading a book about how to drive a car and actually driving a car on the road with other drivers, dealing with stop lights, road signs and other bad drivers. Just as NOT everyone is cut out to be a Network Admin, so also not everyone is cut out to be Doctors, Accountants, Mechanics, Chefs, etc. AI will certainly make it easier to learn these skills, but it won't easily replace the people who currently perform such tasks. And the better you are, the harder it will be to replace you. AI may lower the bar for entry, but it won't remove the bar entirely. 

Last thought: The threat is certainly there; it's just that, in my estimation, it's non-existential. If AI were to take over the functions of many (if not most human beings), it would take a long time. A slow, gradual shift, which would 1: Give the rest of us time to learn a new trade, 2: It would also produce new job sectors specific to the changes brought about by AI as it gains greater acceptance. Sweeping changes like this happen periodically; look at the Agricultural Revolution, or the Industrial revolution. (Check out the story of the Luddites, if you don't already know it.) There are certainly more jobs now than there were when the Luddites complained about machine-driven textile plants; their entire industry was wiped out and remade using new-found technology. Sure, AI will change the way we work and live, but we will adapt. Technology has always been a delicate dance; sometimes it steps on our toes, but in the end, it's better to show up than to miss the dance entirely.

In a post-GPT (Generative Pre-training Transformer) world, it may be helpful to focus on developing skills that are difficult for artificial intelligence (AI) to replicate. Some examples of skills that may be valuable in a post-GPT world include:

Creativity: AI models can generate text, music, and art, but they may struggle to come up with truly original and innovative ideas. Developing your creative skills can make you more valuable in a world where AI is increasingly present.
Emotional intelligence: AI models can process and analyze data, but they may struggle to understand and respond to human emotions in the same way that a person can. Developing your emotional intelligence can make you more valuable in roles that require empathy, such as in customer service or management.
Critical thinking: AI models can quickly analyze large amounts of data, but they may not be able to think critically and ask challenging questions in the same way that a person can. Developing your critical thinking skills can make you more valuable in roles that require problem-solving and decision-making.
Interpersonal skills: AI models can communicate via text or voice, but they may not be able to effectively communicate and work with others in the same way that a person can. Developing your interpersonal skills can make you more valuable in roles that require teamwork and collaboration.
In summary, developing skills that are difficult for AI to replicate, such as creativity, emotional intelligence, critical thinking, and interpersonal skills, can help you become more valuable in a post-GPT world.

I asked ChatGPT if it would replace software engineers in the next 5 years and it said this:

‚ÄúNo, software engineers will always be needed to update and create new software. ChatGPT is helpful in understanding user input and responding to it, but AI is still not as capable as human engineers when it comes to creating and updating software.‚Äù

@Alan A Schreier 
Me > Are you familiar with the work of Gustav Mahler?


It > Yes, I am familiar with the work of Gustav Mahler. Mahler was a late-Romantic composer and conductor who was active in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. He was born in Bohemia (now the Czech Republic) in 1860 and spent most of his career working in Austria and Germany. Mahler is known for his symphonies, which are large-scale, multi-movement orchestral works that often incorporate vocal soloists and choir. He was also a prolific composer of lieder (art songs) for solo voice and piano, and wrote several operas and other orchestral works. Mahler's music is characterized by its emotional intensity and its use of folk and popular elements, and his work had a significant influence on the development of 20th-century classical music.

Me > :Do you consider Das Lied von der Erde a symphony, or a song cycle?

It > :Das Lied von der Erde (The Song of the Earth) is a composition by Gustav Mahler that is sometimes referred to as a symphony, but it is actually a song cycle for tenor and contralto soloists and orchestra. It is based on a collection of Chinese poetry translated into German, and the texts of the songs reflect on the themes of transience, loss, and the beauty of nature. The work is structured in six movements, with the vocal soloists singing the texts of the poems in each movement. The instrumentation is similar to that of a symphony, with a large orchestra including strings, woodwinds, brass, and percussion, but the work is more closely related to the genre of the song cycle, which involves a series of individual songs that are connected by a common theme or narrative.

Me > :Many people, myself included, consider Das Lied von der Erde to be a symphony; Mahler called it ‚ÄúA symphony of song.‚Äù

It > :Yes, it is common for Das Lied von der Erde to be referred to as a symphony, and Mahler himself referred to it as "A symphony of song." While the work is structured in six movements and has a large orchestra similar to a symphony, it is also distinct from a traditional symphony in that it includes solo vocal parts and is based on a series of poems rather than being purely instrumental. As such, it is often considered to be a hybrid of a symphony and a song cycle. Ultimately, the way a particular work is classified can depend on how it is perceived and described by listeners, performers, and scholars, and different people may have different opinions on how to label a given piece of music.

Me > : I think you are correct, that it is a hybrid 

It > : It's good to hear that you agree with my assessment of Das Lied von der Erde as a hybrid of a symphony and a song cycle. As I mentioned earlier, the way a particular work is classified can depend on how it is perceived and described by listeners, performers, and scholars, and different people may have different opinions on how to label a given piece of music. The important thing is to appreciate the work for its own unique qualities and characteristics, regardless of how it is classified.

***end of transcription ***

You don't seem to understand what AI is, or what software engineering is.  Translating from "well defined" natural language to programming language is not the hard part of software engineering.  Software engineering is taking vague requirements, requirements sometimes the customers themselves don't even know about, and build a solution using software.  In other words, do what they think not what they say.  That is vastly different from "write a function to compute the fft of some input" or "compute the nth fib series".  These are well defined statements, and it is basically a google search at this point, just very advanced google search.  Or stack overflow search.
There used to be a exercise in a first course on computer science that asks all the students new to CS to write an algorithm to tell a computer how to make a peanut butter sandwich...  The result is no one produced an algo that a computer can use to do something so simple.  The problem is computers are very dumb, and does exactly what you tell it.  This last part is why AI is not true AI, it does "exactly" what you tell it, no more, no less.   
ChatGPT can produce some impressive code, but the issue is it doesn't actually understand the code it produces.  And more importantly, it doesn't actually know the right answer, just the most probable answer based on training data.  It is not capable of internalizing reality and run simulations on the internal model of reality, aka Einstein's thought experiment.  So while it looks to us as intelligent, it is just collating massive amounts of data and give you the most probable "right" answer that may or may not be correct.
So no, AI of this type, no matter how advanced, can never replace actual software engineers.

The "terrifying"  fear and anxiety this author is propagating is based on ignorance of history and economics, as I will show. 

Workers have been fretting that machinery/automation is going to cause mass unemployment since the 1600s when the weavers started destroying the new weaving looms in protest. There aren't going to be any weavers! They're all going to starve!

Same with the early Industrial Revolution, 1820s. We need to panic because all the new machinery/automation is going to cause mass chronic unemployment. 

Didn't happen, did it?

I remember in the 1980s when the panic du jour was the idea that computers are going to tip everyone out of work.

Didn't happen, did it? 

Horses being replaced by cars? Post being replaced by email? The list goes on. 

So let's just stop and THINK for a minute. 

Why did the "terrifying" anxiety-provoking scenarios not actually happen?

The reasons is because, the displaced workers went on to do something HIGHER VALUE. They did things that people PREFER, more than expensive hand-woven cloth, horses instead of cars, and so on. 

While ever human effort is capable of satisfying human wants, you have nothing to worry about. 

It is not "quite terrifying" that people will be "valued for their human bodies". All work requires the use of one's body to do it. 

The march of technology will not cause the feared employment apocalypse in the future, any more than it did in the past. 

Just take the hype level down, don't worry, smell the roses, plan for tomorrow while you live for today. 

Click-bait lives by sensationalism and hype. That's more of a danger to your life than mere increased automation.

It is important for software engineers to keep up with new technologies and tools, but it is unlikely that they will be replaced by them.

I just tried to use chatgtp. Here is my experience paraphrased:

It gave me a correct program when I told it to make a script that doubles a Fibonacci number, but the example run it gave was incorrect. I said "your code is correct, but the example was completely wrong, the real answer for your program was 110, not 188". 

It said oh oops, fib(10) is 34. Here's a program that outputs it correctly (same program but without the doubling).

I said "that outputs 55, not 34".

It said "oh oops, you're right that it outputs 55. Here's a program that outputs 34: (exact same program)."

I said "that was just the same program again"

It said "oh oops, you're right that it's the same program. Here is a program that will output 34:" (same program, still outputs 55)

I said "but that program outputs 100" (a complete lie)

It said: "oh oops, you're correct that that program outputs 100. Here's a program that outputs 34:" (same program).

I think with this simple example, we can see that more needs to be engineered. Probabilistic text prediction can't stand up to anyone giving it a hard time. It's possible openai engineers make an "understanding" AI in the future, but that would be new R&D, not something that will reliably happen soon.

The reason gpt has advanced so quickly, from my limited understanding, was that they trained it on more and more data, they didn't make anything super new and smart. I wouldn't say a "post gpt world", because gpt is not the technology that will kill these engineers. It would be a post "understanding AI" world, which has a wayy more variable timeframe.

It is possible that programmers will be mass replaced by AI with a surface level understanding (GPT is inarguably surface level, it's just predicting what to say next based on what has been said last), that would be funny as fuck.

I asked it what "presentation mode" was in xfce, because I didn't know. It said that it was for hiding desktop icons and stuff. It sounded very right and gave a great, in depth explanation.

I looked it up and tried it: what presentation mode actually does is prevent your screen from going to sleep. 

So the AI is wrong, but very confident. Probably very, very good for tricking people, but now I'm never going to use it for the answers to my questions. In hindsight, maybe asking it a niche desktop manager question is a little bit outside of its wheelhouse, but it gave a completely, 100% confident answer nonetheless. I'm very much questioning its medical knowledge now.

Whoops, rereading, it gave Fibonacci (n-1) instead of fib(n) when I lied about the value being 100. That does output 34, but the programs it gave me before that all outputted 55 when it claimed 34. It's contradicting itself now too.

Overall, I still felt like I was talking to a predictive text algorithm.

A few big caveats 1. ChatGPT is very nondeterministic. If you leave a session and come back and give it the same prompt it will give very different code. Sometimes it will be good and sometimes it will be crap 2. More complicated prompts will quickly go beyond its character limit 3. Slight changes in the prompt can lead to huge changes in the code, partially due to #1, so an actual developer will still be necessary to customize and clean up the output

The purpose of chatGPT is to test it on the public. We are training it to only give good outputs. If you tell it to continue unfinished responses it can go beyond the character limit. You have ask it to improve your own inputs for you.

What was interesting to me was its ability to take into account the context of your request before either giving you the information you asked for, or not doing so. For example, I asked which substances would interact with a specific drug in a certain way. The first time, I asked as if the interaction was the desired outcome (i.e. abuse), and it declined to answer, providing an explanation on the importance of taking medications as directed, and how it (the AI) has been trained to prioritize safety. The second time, I asked for the same information, but as someone wanting to avoid accidental overdose as a result of said interaction. This time, the AI gave me the answer I was looking for. While this does show that it isn't too difficult to manipulate the language model into giving you the answer you desire, it's definitely more advanced than previous systems that would simply answer any question. I think one of the most impressive feats they have achieved is managing to not only develop a language model of this level, but also guide its learning in a way that reduces harm without crippling its capabilities (at least most of the time, sometimes it really just gives away the political leanings of whoever had the most influence on this aspect of the model). From what I've read, GPT-4 is somewhere on the horizon, so I have no doubt that we're going to be surprised once again by how far the technology has advanced when we eventually get to play with it. Oh, and if you want a job that will exist in a decade's time, something in a field like AI ethics would probably fit the bill.

It is difficult to predict exactly how AI will evolve and be used in the future, but it is unlikely that it will be able to fully replace software engineers. While AI systems can be very good at automating certain tasks and processing large amounts of data, they lack the creativity, problem-solving skills, and judgment of a human software engineer.

Software engineering involves a wide range of tasks that require a strong understanding of computer science principles and the ability to apply them in a practical setting. It also involves the ability to think creatively and come up with innovative solutions to problems. These tasks require a level of cognitive flexibility and adaptability that AI systems are not yet capable of.

That being said, it is possible that AI systems could be used to assist software engineers in their work in the future, by automating certain tasks or providing recommendations based on data. However, it is unlikely that AI will be able to fully replace the expertise and judgment of a human software engineer.

Dude... take a breath. Make some tea. Everything will be okay.  Why? Because people have been predicting the "demise" of human knowledge workers for 100 years. This is no different. ChatGPT is not what you think. It's essentially a fancier version of Google, Alexa, or Siri. Have they made your job obsolete? Laughable, right? They only _enhance_ what you are capable of, and that's the key. Employees of billion dollar companies today scrape sample bits of code off Stackoverflow and other places on the internet, as I'm sure you do, and everything works out. But, there is human oversight to ensure it is sensible in the context of the part of the code it is being added to, that it does exactly what is needed, and not more, that it is tested as working, etc. ChatGPT is not going to do this.  

Think of it like this:  30 years ago, circa 1992, if you had showed someone how modern Google works, and how it could instantly provide nearly limitless information on any topic you could possibly think of, including images, etc, they would be mindblown. They would right then and there predict the downfall of all jobs and perhaps even some utopian paradise where "all humans know all things".  But we have Google now. Has it happened? Lol. Of course not. In fact, some would say it has actually dumbed down our society. (And in fact it, along with social media, has been used to do the opposite: To spread DIS-information to a wide population, especially in politics, to get them to elect unqualified leaders and mount government insurrections.)

So that is where we are at with ChatGPT.  Same deal. We are experience the "wow" moment of seeing something that appears to be amazing for the first time. Then years later, you realize it was just another tool to enable humans to do what they do better and faster.  Nothing more. Human knowledge workers in the next 5 year, 10 years, 30 years will still be just as needed, just as overworked, just as critical to the day to day operations of businesses as they are today.

So what will happen with ChatGPT after the silly viral phase?  Same thing that happened to Google, Siri and Alexa, and GPS, and Google Maps, and Google Earth, and all the other "amazing" technologies. They just fade into the background and become integrated into our society as just another "meh" everyday thing. And kids 10 years from now will never have known a world where tools like ChatGPT didn't exist and it will have no "wow" effect for them, just as Gen-Z kids today use Google like the rest of us would use a fork.

But here's my prediction. Why isn't the entire world freaking out about other content creation AI systems like Jasper and others? It's because they put up pay-walls. That will kill the technology from normal public use as soon as the "guinea pig" phase of public ingestion of questions and chosen answers is over and they start trying to make people pay for this as a commercial service. Then boom. Gone.  This isn't Netflix. People would never have used Google or any of the popular social media platforms if they'd had to shell out a monthly subscription. And that is where this OpenAI stuff is headed. It's too costly to maintain, as the information it consumes grows exponentially without a subscription model. And the only people paying for those future subscriptions will be larger companies and content creators, not high school kids trying to cheat on their school assignments. And it will go the way of Jasper as well.  Only until a company finds a way to monetize it with Ads will it potentially become integrated into everyone's daily lives.  That means the people who would use it for good and those who would use it for evil and illegal gain. Same as all of human history.  So don't worry.  Nothing will change.  It will eventually be just another "fork" to humanity.

I don't know. My browser's search bar has been writing code for years in the form of links to StackOverflow. I'm not convinced ChatGPT is as much of a leap beyond that as the initial wow factor makes one think.

And I'm not sure how well it does at attending to the details of the requirements I try to give it. For instance, I like asking it to write poems involving a particular list of words, because the peculiar juxtapositions and turns of phrase it comes up with are often hilarious. Now in form, the poems are always doggerel of the most appalling kind, but perhaps style doesn't matter if it gets the job done. Yet when it disregarded the particulars of my request to include three different words for shades of green, and included close to ten of them instead, I've got to take issue with that. Poetic license is one thing, but what if this had been a business rule where the exact value of n mattered? If GPT feels free to reinterpret requirements like this, without even letting me know directly that it's done so, somebody's going to have to go over the code it writes very carefully.

I'm sure the technology will get better, but I think it still has a very long ways to go if it's ever going to be trusted to produce a large amount of high-quality code from requirements expressed in natural language, while asking intelligent questions to clarify anything that needs it. And I have found that bots have enormous gaps in common sense, which can shatter their facade of genius in one sometimes hilarious but often exasperating instant.
Well, the next industrial revolution won't be a labor revolution, will be an intelectual one. Artist, writers, programmers, economists, etc etc may lose their jobs in the next 5 to 10 years.

It's going to be much longer than 5 years. Writing individual functions with fixed and well defined scope is a different matter than fully fleshing out an architecture. Even if the writing of code becomes 100% automated, there will still remain a need for skill workers to clarify requirements and verify+validate code drafted by an algorithm. A more realistic set of expectations is that within 5 years a number of businesses will integrate ML-assisted development where engineers are drafting technical requirements derived from business requirements and writing integration and unit tests that any generated code must successfully pass.

Engineers will also still be required to maintain proficiency in reading generated code as well. A simple demonstration for this is to imagine prompting the creation of a subroutine to perform a task in an esoteric language like brainf*ck. You might get perfectly fine code from the ML algorithm, but if you can't read brainf*ck then you have little means to claim confidence that there are no obvious cornercases that have been missed. A lot of engineers used to have these same concerns when moving away from low-level languages and machine code fearing that the compiler would put them out of a job, but the reality is that compilers just freed engineers to focus on more abstract higher level problem domains. That will happen here too, with engineers writing less functional code and focusing more on testing and architecture.

I have been tossing a variety of testing problems, and some code problems at it.
It falls apart faster than you demonstrate it does.
The examples you are using can be fished out of stackexchange and a variety of other code mill dumps.
There are a lot of stock patterns which are easy for ChatGPT to scotch tape together to provide compilable, working answers.

It is impressive in its ability to infer all sorts of ideas from plain language, but it still makes big mistakes when the logic to solve a problem is a combination of novel and requires following a logical trail more than the immediate surface information. It works great on "code from example", but not so good on "good from the implications of the example"

Another behavior that is lacking is the independent ability to drill-in. It also does not ask clarifying questions. Both of these behaviors are critical to any knowledge worker succeeding in their task, and both are somewhat hard to mechanize because drilling in and clarifying questions operate against an infinity of possibilities - when to stop, where to start? If a person gives a ten part answer to a question, which of those ten parts do you ask for clarification on, how do you discern if those ten parts are good answers or not, if they are just repeat of the same class? My investigation thus far is ChatGPT avoids this problem entirely - and I believe part of it is because of this infinite iteration problem.

To illustrate how this AI uses the language of maths and the appearance of reasoning to draw completely incorrect conclusions, here are two conversation snippets.

Round 1, where I didn't actually give it enough information to define h, but it failed to realise this and confidently gave nonsensical answers, though it got some basic arithmetic right. 
Me: If h(x) = 2*h(2*x), find h(1).
GPT: We can evaluate the value of h(1) by substituting 1 for x in the equation h(x) = 2h(2x). This gives us the equation h(1) = 2h(21). Substituting 2 for the value of 2x in the original equation, we get h(1) = 2h(2) = 4h(4) = 8h(8) = ...
This pattern continues indefinitely, with each subsequent value of h being double the previous value. Since h(1) is the first value in this sequence, it must be equal to 1. Therefore, the value of h(1) is 1.
 
 
Me: What is the value of h(0)?
GPT: Substituting 0 for x in the equation h(x) = 2h(2x), we get h(0) = 2h(20). Substituting 0 for the value of 2x in the original equation, we get h(0) = 2h(0) = 4h(0) = 8h(0) = ...
This pattern continues indefinitely, with each subsequent value of h being double the previous value. Since h(0) is the first value in this sequence, it must be equal to 1. Therefore, the value of h(0) is 1.
 
 
Me: That is incorrect. Since h(0) = 2*h(2*0) = 2*h(0), we have that h(0) = 0.
GPT: You are correct. I apologize for my mistake. Substituting 0 for x in the equation h(x) = 2h(2x) gives us h(0) = 2h(20). Substituting 0 for the value of 2x in the original equation gives us h(0) = 2h(0). Since the value of h(0) appears on both sides of the equation, we can set the two sides equal to each other to get h(0) = 2*h(0).
Since h(0) cannot be both 0 and not 0 at the same time, it must be the case that h(0) = 0. Therefore, the value of h(0) is 0.

Round 2, where I was a little kinder, and it got h(0) right for the wrong reasons, and h(2) completely wrong.
Me: h(x) = 2*h(2*x). h(1) = 1. Find h(0) and h(2).
GPT: To find h(0), we plug 0 into the equation for h(x) to get h(0) = 2 * h(0 * 2), which simplifies to h(0) = 2 * h(0). Since any number multiplied by 0 is 0, we have h(0) = 2 * 0 = 0.
To find h(2), we plug 2 into the equation for h(x) to get h(2) = 2 * h(2 * 2), which simplifies to h(2) = 2 * h(4). Since we know that h(1) = 1, we can use this information to find h(4) by plugging 1 into the equation for h(x): h(4) = 2 * h(1 * 2) = 2 * h(2) = 2 * 2 * h(1) = 2 * 2 * 1 = 4. Therefore, h(2) = 2 * h(4) = 2 * 4 = 8.
In summary, h(0) = 0 and h(2) = 8.

I spent some time with ChatGPt two days ago.

One of the caveats that are clearly pointed out in the introduction is that the program is optimized for natural-language modeling. It is NOT optimized to provide correct answers. The developers warn about this prior to trying the ChatBot. To say this another way, the object of the software is to provide answers in a way that mimics (stylistically) what you might receive from a human. They are intended to appear to be good answers (syntax and grammar) but the answers might be wrong.

I asked it one question that I subsequently forgot but it produced an answer something like this. "I am optimized for language modeling but I am not connected to the Internet so I am not qualified to do the research needed to answer your question."

I asked, "Are you good at playing chess?" The answer I received was something like it does not possess Artificial Intelligence and therefore is unable to learn to play chess without being programmed to do so."

As far as this ChatBot is concerned, there are some major limitations. However, this is in its infancy. I read of many predicting that this will replace most if not all of the people currently doing this kind of work.

There is a greater demand now for graphic artists than at any time in history.

Therefore, it is more likely that AI will augment the work of programmers, helping them to be more efficient and productive, rather than replacing them entirely.

Just because a chatbot can generate medical text does not mean it can perform surgery. There's a big difference between generating the text and understanding it.

You should really research what Natural Language Generation (NLG) is. It's essentially a formula for what the next word is, based on the previous words. That's all it is, a formula, using probabilities it discovered from training data. It has no concept of the meaning behind those words, or how it would convert that medical text to a surgery.

You could theoretically hook up chatGPT to another AI that can convert the text into actions. That process is called Natural Language Understanding (NLU), like how you can tell Google Assistant to book you reservations. As far as I know, that's about how far we are now: making reservations, turning appliances on and off. Nowhere near complex surgery.

It's just another tool. It's not like a client is going to start typing prompts and get a fully working, tested, and deployed application that meets all requirements. They wouldn't even know what prompts to write. They don't even know what they want for god's sake.

Writing code is just a fraction of software engineering.

Okay I can see why you are terrified. I am too. But let me give you my perspective as someone who is a technology worker. 
What this means is that we all get to give ourselves a promotion. You now have a research intern working for you who can retrieve any information you want, summarize information for you, verify it, write reports, explain things, compare information, and search things. 
Now what chatgpt does for you is only limited by 
1. Your ability to interact with it, and at what level you engage it. 
2. Your ability to understand what it is saying and act on the information

Imagine a Phd scholar. If a highschooler talks with it, the Phd will give simple answers. But if another scholar and this Phd person meet, the scholar will be able to ask probing questions and have a scholarly discussion. 
You can't just ask chatGPT to give you the plans to build a fortune500 company. It is going to ask you ok, which field? We are not at AGI levels. And even if we were talking with general intelligence, few would have the patience to act on the multi year plan this all-knowing super intelligence would spit out.

As a developer I feel so much more powerful now. The days of searching internet forums for obscure problems and troubleshooting are over. You don't have to search google, scan a medium article to get to that little bit of problem youre facing. I don't have to read documentations of libraries and APIs. THIS IS POWER. 

ChatGPT is a generative model. It is generating things for you. But from where? Latent space. Give a million monkeys typewriters and a billion years, and they will eventually write the entire works of sheakspere. The space of infinite possibility is that latent space. A feature space of a billion and more coordinates/dimensions. Machine Learning is the way computers navigate this latent space. Hidden here are beautiful pieces of art, groundbreaking science, and horrors unimaginable. Here's the catch...machines can't navigate this latent space on their own. They need humans to guide them through it. Like the seers in the Dune series.

I work in machine learning and currently help build these sorts of models and applications, and I personally don't think this will make software engineers obsolete, though it will certainly impact them. These models are fantastic at writing code, no doubt. However, they aren't ready to pipe together applications. You will still need to have engineers who will have to put together applications by piecing code together. And sure, chatGPT can provide guidance to that end, but I think we will still end up relying on humans to make final decisions (and I don't think most managerial folks are technically competent enough to do that either). Consider the cost of running this model as well. Right now, you see it as a free service, but openAI is incurring heavy costs for running this model. GPT3 costs money per token. So it is not like this will not become expensive eventually when openAI flips the switch and turns it into a paid service (as they always do). Compare this to the cost of hiring a team of engineers. A team of engineers will likely cost more, but with a team of engineers, you also get people who will maintain your code, understand best optimizations, and understand best ways to implement business logic. I do think we will come to a time where not as many engineers are needed. For example, with something like chatGPT bundled into a swe-focused application, you could likely cut an engineering team in half or more. The ones who will survive are the ones who can think beyond code snippets (hardcode leetcode warriors will bite the dust, at last!). I don't see this happening in the industry in the next 5 years, however. I would put it on a 10-15 year horizon, depending on the sector. Banking and more conservative businesses will likely implement such a structure last as they have tight security constraints and trust is of utmost importance there. Regardless, software engineers are here to stay, just in a more transformed role. I think whether or not this plays out will depend on the final costs of chatGPT. 

Additionally, chatGPT and similar models don't have a sense of truth. They are generative models that generate text on the most probable next token. So they can occasionally spit out false information. Professions in medicine or science cannot reliably use these applications as sources of truth, especially given the nature of their work where life may be at risk. Can we build fact checking applications on top of it? Sure. However, human judgement will always be the final stop in a chain of decisions in these fields. 

I think the areas that chatGPT will definitely make people obsolete are copywriting, editing, customer service - any job that was not automated due to challenges of textual nuance, will now be on the chopping block.

@The LoveJoy Show We are no where near the point where machines can think for themselves. It feels that way simply because of the structure of these models and the fact that they were trained on human data. However, these models do not think, nor do they work in the same way brains do. Can we reach it one day? Sure, but on more of a 100 year timeline.

To me it seems that the capabilities of chatGPT are starting to approach that of a Star Trek computer - which is not necessarily a bad thing. The most optimistic case is that systems like chatGPT will be an invaluable and always available assistant that helps you to make your ideas a reality.
It will certainly impact the way we are working - especially in the knowledge economy. The way children and young adults need to be prepared for this future needs to be defined. Highly specialized and specific knowledge has always been a dangerous thiing, easily becoming obsolete or entrenched. In my opinion, what's necessary now is to really focus education on the "big picture'", on making the connections between different fields of knowledge clear, thus enabling future employees, researchers etc. to create new connections, bring new ideas into the world. AI of the chatGPT type will probably be challenged to do that. It can make simple connections between exisiting concepts and summarize knowledge admirably, but it's lacking in the creative department - the creation of code is no contradiction to that, after all it was probably trained on decades of GitHub and Stackoverflow content (there's even a rather intriguing issue of circular reasoning and knowledge entrenchment lurking should more and more code on these platforms be generated by chatGPT; in some ways it  leads to circular reasoning and finally to knowledge stagnation).
For the time being, and also at least for the next decade, I absolutely expect new and disruptive ideas will still exclusively spawn from human minds.
Code monkeys, however, should take note. They could indeed become obsolete within a very short timeframe.

Yesterday I discover it had trouble generating a list of randomized names that currently do not exist. At first it said it wasn‚Äôt connected to the internet and couldn‚Äôt draw on a larger pool of resources to produce more unique names. Basically it kept producing the same results that were names I had heard before with a slight modification at the end, over and over again. I again asked why it was producing only those names with slight modifications and it explained how the language model it uses generates names and why my request was producing that list. It said to adjust how I was asking and it would attempt to produce a better randomized list of unique names. That led me to probing the requests I was making and finding a work around by stipulating a series of requirements when creating brand new names. I had it randomly choose 5 adjectives and then draw 5 Human names that it‚Äôs language model produced with those adjectives. It was then required to take sections of those human names at staggered intervals and recombine the pieces back together in a way the phonetically resembled the English language to produce 10 brand new names. It worked really well. Kind of interesting that it can help me get it to do something that it wasn‚Äôt fully intended to do.

@R D But ChatGPT is a natural language model, it's just good at generating output that's looks plausibly like its training material. If it has any definition of correctness, it's how similar its output looks to what it's already seen ... it can't come up with iteratively better solutions based on some complex/arbitrary criteria like how well a website works, or how well a backend service meets some custom acceptance criteria - that sounds like more the domain of artificial general intelligence, which afaiu natural language processing definitely is not.

All a project needs is a definition of correctness. Once it knows how to determine that one outcome is preferred over a different outcome, then it is just a matter of setting it up to compete with itself. Write a solution one way, then write the solution a slightly different way and compare which is better. Do that a few million times and it can surely arrive at a functional solution to arbitrarily complex problems.

I was thinking the same thing. At the same time though: entire solutions are not that much more complicated. It's just a specification of infrastructure that you launch in the cloud, some API definitions and some services implementing it with some logic. If this is where we are now, it is not at all unimaginable that within five years we can have it create a git repo with a setup that includes such boilerplate.

The more complex parts are probably about teaching it about legacy code. GPT relies on patterns it finds in large text corpora, whereas individual code bases usually break away from mainstream patterns in all kinds of surprising ways. I'll be worried if I see it refactor existing code in a way that it consistently improves the quality :P

I don't agree with this take for a few reasons, as it seems rather hyperbolic. I do agree some lower level tasks will be replaced and there may be some disruptions in certain spaces in certain industries, however. These are my counterpoints - 

1. Attribution of responsibility: Humans need someone to blame or to take the mantle of responsibility for.

 When shit goes wrong, no one wants to be repeatedly querying an API chat interface with a million prompts to specifically get a return value which resolves a problem. The diffusion of responsibility prevents most important work from being something that is out of the control of a team or individual contributor to the solution at hand.

You need someone to be assigned a role and to complete said role so that humans can feel comfortable. Until we can acheive this with absolute confidence, you would at a minimum - need to retain people who understand the problem sufficiently to query the AI and therefore produce an outcome (such as integrating code snippets generated), and to hold them to completion of tasks. The AI won't just 'write itself' - you still need intelligent prompting. 

Even if I were to take this example 5 years in the future: Will ChatGPT really be able to do this?

Hey ChatGPT, can you produce a complete replica of your frontend and backend binaries and provide them to me in an easy to use .exe on a windows 11 machine?

(Recursively ask it to do absurd things like make a full stack visualization engine which takes in buisness data and give me the 'correct buisness decision', invent algorithms which perform faster searches than binary search, write the chemical sequence of a drug that cures cancer)

This doesn't even begin to consider the use cases where no data would ever be permitted to interface with an externally broadcasting/conencted nerual network - such as defense, medical records, bank or credit transactions, user information and details which are personal and protected by law. 

2. Depth of comprehension: I can read it, it does not mean I can reproduce the desired outcome.

In your example of the surgery, you present an argument that the words you read are sufficient to perform said surgery with any degree of reliability. I disagree completely. I can 'read' a book on how to code, but I wouldn't know how to code. I could read a book on identifying rare diseases, it doesn't mean I would be able to take a sample, go to a lab, perform all the experiments myself and conclude that the disease was in fact Ebola. 

Yes, where code is concerned it is slightly problematic, but in truth - how many software engineers spend 100% of their time churning out actual new feature code? I dare say more than half the time it is fixing bugs, resolving tickets, updating or upgrading to new refactored standards, meetings to understand  and assign work being distributed in a team and to give assurance that the client vision and outcome are aligned. In essence, humans are an interpreter that take abstracted human language inputs and transform them into a product. 

You're essentially claiming that software engineers would not be necessary and that perhaps one of the 'few' maintainers could type in a single prompt, or perhaps, several prompts to generate a working product. I don't agree with that - even if we could make functions more quickly, who is going to be prompting for the correct functions and subsequently adjusting it to meet the exact use cases? It's still software engineers, right? They're paid highly because they understand notions like what is memory, what are functions even, what is a data structure, what is typing, what is recursive, what is a binary tree, what is dynamic programming, what are API calls, networking, unix, linux, filestructures - it goes on and on and on. 

This cannot be precluded from the prompt if anyone wants something useful. As they say, garbage in - garbage out. No romance author will be able to create a useful function without understanding those underlying concepts - and if they're really so easy to pick up, and the hard part was abstracting it into code - then maybe that's a good thing, so we can all progress from a world where you google for hours and pray 1 man 15 years ago saw the light to an arcane and obscure problem caused by bad code to one where I complete a 'hard task' in 1 hour rather than days.

In fact if it promulgates a world where standardized efficient prompted code is the norm: "Hey ChatGPT, using the OPENAI_PYTHON_STANDARD_2022_12_1 standard, generate code which takes in excel data and computes the mean, median and mode of each column, and marks them with the original labels, and use the standard visualiztion output standard OPENAI_SCIKIT_VIZ_STANDARD_2022_12_1 to plot the 20 most popular available plots and present them in order of popularity!" - I would consider this a godsend, because that's 90% of the nonsense meetings about what to show in a visualization, what is popular, and what standards to adopt and what nonsense approach did another engineer take in the past, so we should use that for consistency bullshit to be gone. Your sprint tasks are over in 2 days instead of 2 weeks, and the other 12 days you can spend teaching other people or even just enjoying collaborative experiences which HR loves to tell us to go for.

3. Physicality of the world and human hierarchy: We still need a person to go interact with things so they happen.

Knowledge workers are not just sitting on their ass and getting stuff done by typing away. The human-in-the-loop system many industries employ, such as air-gapped environments, visiting a data centre, confirmation of the outcome, performing actual surgery, taking samples, taking an interview, attending a meeting, proactively asking the right questions are all still parts of everyone's job. Even the most introverted software engineer has to attend company events/all hands and standups to receive and delegate tasks. 

Until we automate away managers - workers will not be automated away, this is something I am sure of. The CEO is not going to be figuring out how ChatGPT works and trying to replace his secretary with it. Likely he will force his underlings - who will delegate continually down the chain until they make some team (the engineers probably) responsible for using this tool to improve outcomes. The managers and their managers will still have to retain some semblance of utility, and if there are no workers - unless the CEO is okay with talking tech at a deep level across every domain - test, developer, platform, network, security, buisness analysis, project management, finance, accounts - he will need managers - who in turn will need their workers to figure the stuff out they cant or wont.

The laziness principle will certainly ensure that we will retain many of the 'fluff' jobs, because that's how human behaviour works. More people - more headcount - more important. Very few organizations  and industries will be able to streamline to such a degree as to be able to produce meaningful outcomes with very few hands. This tool, as I see it, is more like super excel. We will have a new class of workers who will learn to use the tool to its maximal potential and yield its fruits, and they will be from all domains. But! No human will be permitted to take on so much responsibility as to become 'indispensable'. The system will continue to survive, even if more people do less work. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parkinson%27s_law

"I agree with the counterpoints made in the response. While it is true that AI and automation can take over some tasks and make certain processes more efficient, it is unlikely that they will completely replace human developers in the near future. There are several reasons for this.

I think that this could be a useful tool for us developers, a tool to be more productive and to have more knowledge in different fields, but I don't think that this could replace our job. The main problem is that is limited to the complexity of your instruction it cannot go beyond and see "the big picture", but only on a detailed level, and sometimes is not even 100% correct.
