@HRN Thank you.  I think in the next 5 years, we'll come to understand the limits and capabilities of the current batch of machine learning systems.  I think that the reach of machine learning will spread.  Right now, the systems are applied rather generically, but I anticipate that in the next 5 years, we'll see a lot of domain specific machine learning that will rapidly accelerate those domains.  For example, in artistry, right now 2-D images are being produced from description.  But I think I see that within 5 years time, a machine learning system specifically trained towards creating 3-D animations of creatures, based on previously constructed 3-D animations of creatures, will be able to create full animated sequences for creatures, from written description.  So I think that this is going to be a highly disruptive technology.

It is plausible to me that software development will see similar kinds of development.  But something that is coming out is that mathematical reasoning is presently not something that these large data statistical systems work with very well.  There is the "explain your reasoning step by step" technique that produces better answers, but they're still producing wrong answers, and they very much do NOT learn from mistakes.  I have experimented with this a number of times, and the replies can be quite comical.  "I don't know why I get it wrong, I just do.  I can't help it," -- it said something to me like that once.

I do think that we will see general artificial intelligence one day.  I would estimate in the 20-50 year time frame.  This kind of general synthetic intelligence would be able to deeply understand things, hold understandings in a working memory, would learn from mistakes and prevent future mistakes.  But I don't anticipate this in the 5-10 year time frame.

What I see is a lot of people (including the Google engineer I mentioned prior) getting overwhelmed with the magic of the new technology, and over-projecting onto it.  I think we are nearing the crest of the Gartner Hype Cycle, with respect to these machine learning systems.

The Gartner Hype Cycle does NOT end with failure; It ends with success.  But it's not the same success people envision at the peak, and the effects are different than people expect.

Your claim is that GPT-3 Chat is "coding."  My claim is that, to the contrary, it's regurgitating what it's seen before, and that that's different than coding.

That's the goal post: "Is it coding, or not?"

That's the unmoving goalpost.  What I'm doing is "checking your badge."  I want to know whether you have the qualifications to make an evaluation.

So, what I'm hearing is -- you started programming when you were 13.  I doubt you were professionally programming at that point, so lets say you started programming professionally at 20.  You answer 23 years to my question of how long you've been programming professionally, so I am inferring that you're either 36 years old, if you're counting from when you were 13, when you first started programming and simultaneously started professionally programming -- OR, you are about 43 years old, and you've been programming professionally from when you were say 20.

I'm a little surprised to hear that you think that GPT-3 is genuinely coding, rather than copying things it was exposed to in training, with that 23 years of experience.

BUT, Blake Lemoine reasoned that LaMDA is conscious, because it tells him that it "enjoys talking with its friends and family" in between executing reply() function executions, so, I guess intelligent people CAN get this stuff radically wrong.

In my experience of playing with GPT-3, the code that it returns is sophomoric at best.  It 100% resembles sample code for beginners.  It often just plain doesn't work.  It's so bad that Stack Overflow has BANNED ChatGPT-based contributions, because it is full of errors.  To take your own words -- writing a wrapper around something is a quick and easy task.  So, ChatGPT's contribution of writing a wrapper around something, is absolutely minimal.

What's wrong with beginner code?  Beginner code will just f.write("..."); f.close().  Beginners don't think that they need to write to a temporary file, copy the temporary file onto the destination, and then delete the temporary file.  Beginners don't think about how bytes delivered in TCP packets might not all arrive in the same packet.  The code that I've seen emitted by ChatGPT is fine as a starting point, in many cases?  But it doesn't take that code to maturity, and that's where the bulk of the programmer's work is.  Programmers need to design systems, and the tradeoffs of systems, and implement the working systems.  Alternatively, programmers need to adapt very large code bases.  Can you show me the example where GPT-3 takes in a moderately sized system -- say, just a small 100-200 file project, and extend it in intelligent ways?  I'm still waiting for that one.

My experience is that GPT-3 is something like a fake intelligence.  It produces eye-popping results, "wow!", but then with just a little bit of digging, it is very quickly stumped, and all kinds of limitations show up.

I am an artist, work in traditional and digital media. Currently work in games/vfx/animation. Sculpt in clay, draw, etc. But also love technology, so naturally I am 20k images into Midjourney and have dabbled with Dalle2. What you are saying fits with my experience using Midjourney. It is astoundingly powerful with single subject images, i.e. '/imagine zombie spiderman drawn by Frank Franzetta', but where it struggles is in doing actual illustrations that feature multiple characters performing different actions, in a complicated non-typical environment (and the more specific you are, the more it seems to struggle). If I wanted a scene with two characters walking across dry grassland, character a is smiling, character b is laughing and pointing upwards, character a looks like actor a, character b looks like actor b but at age 60, walking with a futuristic jeep to their left, large baobab trees nearby on the right side of the image while standing inside a giant Halo-torus structure where lakes and rivers flow above them and trees grow upside down, they crane their necks as they watch deer drink from a lakeside that is upside down from their viewpoint, absolutely not. Maybe you could get that specific scene if you described it as seperate elements, but it would still take a fairly well trained artist to assemble those components together and actually art direct the final piece. That's not that say Midjourney can't crank out photo-real images that look like they're movie-stills from a parallel universe, I am just suggesting at this point really art directing each figure, object, etc in that image just does not seem to be possible.  Not to go on too long of a tangent, if there were developers who seeks to empower rather than replace artists with an AI-assisted art tool, it seems like it would blow Midjourney and Dalle2 out of the water.

The simplicity in what he was instructing the model to do makes me highly skeptical that this guy is a senior engineer anywhere. I‚Äôm a senior engineer myself, I‚Äôm largely focused on system design and architecture now. I‚Äôve been using ChatGPT as a sort of google/stack overflow replacement.

First off, no, you cannot ask it to build large scale systems. At least not in its current form. You can‚Äôt for instance ask it to ‚Äúshow me source code for a full stack authentication system using a react front end and express.JS backend‚Äù and expect the code to be exactly that. It simply will list off the steps required to achieve that and then you have to tune your instructions to be much more gradual. For instance I would ask ‚Äúbuild me a docker compose file for a react service, an express.JS service, and a mysql service‚Äù and even then I‚Äôd have to ask follow up instructions to fine tune what I was looking for.

It‚Äôs a fantastic companion to a programmer or any profession really. I have no doubts that with more training and advancements in compute this will improve to be even greater. But to suggest this is capable of eliminating swaths of knowledge workers is just patently false.

But by eliminating a significant part of the job, in terms of number of person hours required to bring a project from idea to production-ready, this will dramatically reduce the demand for engineers. It will simultaneously make the existing population of engineers larger than the market needs. More supply than demand means lower prices, in other words, salaries will plummet for engineers who are able to retain employment.

At some point, AI will make us completely useless in almost every way. We marvel at the advancements made through AI, from self-driving cars and virtual assistants to its use in medical diagnosis. But with current improvements being made, it is only a matter of a little time before AI will be so much better than humans in every way imaginable. This means that our jobs and roles are soon to be taken over by machines, resulting in humans becoming entirely expendable. 

Moreover, human companionship may be significantly affected as people turn more towards their phones for social interaction or entertainment rather than relying on other humans. Already, people have established strong relationships with virtual assistants such as Alexa or Siri - something which would have been unimaginable years ago.

The idea teachers, engineers, or doctors will face obsolescence at the virtual hands of this technology is laughable imo. 

Will jobs be lost? Yes. Will pay be restructured? Absolutely yes. But the idea there will be no jobs in these fields is just goofy gloom and doom; regardless, this is a supplement, a powerful, demi-god of a supplement that still requires expertise and specialized knowledge to return specific results. Even if a layman wants an app to do something specific, they'd still need the vocabulary to articulate that to any given iteration of AI. Even with the eventuality of libraries of queries and prompts, and template responses for specialized needs, people at the executive level of organizations are not going to be monitoring each and every subroutine spawned by AI - someone at some level will have to engage with and troubleshoot this technology one-on-one. 

Horse drivers may have disappeared with the automobile, but they were simply either specialized - Jockeys; or evolved - car drivers/chauffeurs. 

Even in five years there will be a need for people with the skills and knowledge to GUIDE and prompt engineer correctly, and understand the shortcomings of this technology, and derive the desired results. 

If anything this technology is very clearly restructuring people's priorities, and those who think they have no place as artists, musicians, engineers, writers, poets, doctors in a post-ChatGPT world probably are doing themselves a favor by not participating. It's just going to cull a lot of folks from these fields, and boost the productivity and effectiveness of those who remain.

Still a great video, I'm just aggressively optimistic, and in the macro, this is a watershed moment in humanity's history, no doubt - for me after this week there is no going back, 

but when you zoom out, this has happened over and over again in the past, it's just evolution, adapt or die. And things are evolving now at a exponential rate so these world-changing technologies will pop up probably every year in a bit.

The play opens in the court of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table. The knights are gathered around the table, feasting on a hearty meal. Suddenly, a portal opens up in the middle of the room, and out step Rick and Morty.

Rick looks around the room with a puzzled expression on his face, while Morty nervously clings to his arm. The knights of the round table look on in amazement, unsure of what to make of the two strange newcomers.

King Arthur stands up from his seat at the head of the table and approaches Rick and Morty. "Who are you and where do you come from?" he asks in a booming voice.

Rick looks at him with a bored expression and pulls out a flask of alcohol from his pocket. "We're from another dimension, your majesty," he says, taking a swig from the flask. "And we're here to party."

Morty rolls his eyes and pulls on Rick's arm. "Come on, Rick. We should probably get going. These guys don't look like they're into our kind of fun."

But Rick ignores him, and instead turns to the knights of the round table. "So, who wants to play a game of cards? I've got some interdimensional currency that I'm willing to bet."

The knights look at each other in confusion, unsure of how to respond to Rick's offer. But before they can say anything, a loud crashing sound echoes through the room.

The knights look up to see a group of fierce-looking creatures pouring through the portal that Rick and Morty came through. The creatures are armed with weapons and they quickly surround the knights of the round table.

King Arthur pulls out his sword and steps forward to face the creatures. "What is the meaning of this?" he demands.

One of the creatures steps forward and sneers at him. "We've come to take over your world, King Arthur. And there's nothing you and your knights can do to stop us."

Rick and Morty exchange a worried look, and then Rick pulls out a large, futuristic-looking gun from his pocket. He aims it at the creatures and fires, sending them scattering in all directions.

The knights of the round table are amazed by Rick's weapon, and they quickly join in the fight against the invading creatures. Together, they battle their way through the creatures and eventually succeed in driving them back through the portal.

As the portal closes, Rick and Morty look at each other and nod in satisfaction. "Well, that was a close one," Rick says with a grin. "Good thing we showed up when we did."

Morty looks at him with a skeptical expression. "Yeah, I'm sure it had nothing to do with the fact that you accidentally opened the portal in the first place."

Rick just laughs and takes another swig from his flask. "Details, Morty. Details."

The knights of the round table gather around Rick and Morty, grateful for their help in defeating the invading creatures. King Arthur thanks them for their bravery and offers them a place at the round table.

Rick and Morty look at each other, unsure of whether they want to stay in this strange new world. But in the end, they decide to accept King Arthur's offer and take their place at the round table.

And so, the court of King Arthur and the knights of the round table welcome two new members: Rick and Morty, the interdimensional heroes.

I'm a scientist and I don't think ChatGPT will make me obsolete in the next five years. It speaks confidently about topics it is completely wrong about, but unless you're an expect on that field you wouldn't know. For programmers specifically, I think it will change how they work. Similarly to how almost no one codes in assembly now, it's likely that in the future people will work in even higher levels of abstraction than we currently do. However, one reason we write code the way we do is that it allows us to be very precise, and prompting a transformer NN is fundamentally a very vague way of telling a computer what to do. In many cases, actually writing code to solve a problem is easier than explaining what the program should do in words; writing the code is a better way of explaining what the program should do. Finally, when it comes to larger software and not just short scripts, there is still a large gap between the available hardware and the kind of hardware required to run or train a NN with such large inputs. ChatGPT can already process impressively large inputs, but they are a far cry from "write me five million line codebase".

@Peer Svensson Linear doubling and exponential growth are similar in that they both involve an increase by a fixed factor over a period of time, but they are not the same thing. Linear doubling refers to a situation in which a quantity doubles at a constant rate over a given period of time. Exponential growth, on the other hand, is a pattern of growth in which a quantity increases at a rate that is proportional to its current value. This means that the rate of growth increases over time.

For example, if a population is growing linearly, it might double in size every 10 years. If a population is growing exponentially, it might start out growing slowly, but then increase at an increasingly faster rate over time.

In general, exponential growth is characterized by a rapid increase in a quantity over a relatively short period of time, while linear growth is characterized by a slower, more steady increase over a longer period of time.

To the crowd that says "Don't get cozy and judge an AI by it's current abilities, you're not thinking of the exponential growth in x years time". The critical mistake you're all making is assuming the pace of hardware progress to support your doomsday scenarios will continue to follow this exponential growth. Moore's law has nearly reached its limit. Peer Svensson is spot on with his explanation. Knowledge workers will continue to be valuable, it's just that the level of abstraction at which engineers conduct their work in various fields will change, as it always has before. The coding in assembly is a good example. Even embedded engineers today still have frequent reasons to get under the hood and fine tune, tweak, modify, or at the very least, read the assembly to understand what the hardware is actually doing in order to debug and identify the source of a problem or inefficiency. The quality of today's compilers by no means precludes the need for embedded software engineers. @Morgan The "linear doubling function" you wrote is simply a different way to express an exponential series. Let A_k be the k-th number in the series, then the (k+1)-th number in the series is given by A_(k+1) = 2*A_k. Now we can ask the question: what is the N-th number in the series? To answer that we also need to specify where the series starts, so let's say A_1 = 1. Now the N-th number can be written: A_N = 2^(N-1), i.e. as an exponential.

"
Is the number 837=n prime? Show your steps

no.. doubtful that it is true that software engineers will go away, let alone design engineers. I *too* played around with chatGPT and my experience was different. Yes it spit out code for specific functions, but yes it also spit out code for specific functions THAT WAS WRONG. In fact it took me longer to actually debug the code that it spit out than it would have taken for me to write it myself.

In addition, chatGPT tends to hallucinate. For application programming, it spit out code in a language that didn't EXIST (JIRA for example). With software engineers, the huge miss is that 90% of your job is validation and QA, not the original code.

Now it may be true that there are projects that are dealing with this gap right now, but it's a huge long tail to get through them. Figure self-driving cars. Well, 90% of the job of self-driving is fairly easy, it is taking a lot longer that anyone anticipated to tackle that last 10%. Its the same reason btw why automation is taking longer than expected.

Right now, we are at 1970s level where we were with automation and robotics. What's truly terrifying is that chatGPT answers ALL of its questions (right or wrong) with such confidence. Lots of people are going to mistake that confidence for the truth of its claims with I fear disastrous results.

@Greg Mattson I strongly disagree. Google has used AI to develop their nextgen GPUs for model training and they are something like 6 or 8 times faster than A100 boards, and that's just a V1 product. Give them a few more iterations and the processing power will be out of this world. And combine that with continued improvements in AI itself and a feedback loop of sorts is created, where ever increasingly powerful GPUs have more and more power to train smarter and smarter AI, which develop even more powerful GPUs, and so on. At some point in all that, AI will figure out how to do what it needs without humans simply because AI itself will be a better subject to study. The exponential growth in AI basically means that humans will obsolete in a very short amount of time. For example, if AI keeps up with Moore's Law and it doubles its capabilities each year, in 5 years it will be 25 times better than it is today. In 10 years it will be 100 times more capable. I don't see how it doesn't happen...

‚Äã@Morgan the best book I've ever read on AI is 'a thousand brains' by Jeff Hawkins. His main theory is that the neocortex is powered by a bunch of modules in serial which all specialize in various models of parts of the world, that they are constantly updating those models, and that they 'vote' (sample) their outputs to come to conclusions. Our continuous process of learning is all due to the sampling of these models over time. So a part of your brain may be tuned inward (say focused on your amygdala and moderating an emotion) others may be focused on language, others in position of your hands compared to your body.

All of this takes a TREMENDOUS amount of parallelism, computational power, and coordination, which we've inherited over 500 million years of brains. We need to invent that flexibility and coordination, and nothing like that even remotely exists in the AI world. Again, these chat models are really just recombining and outputting stuff that is 'already there', and they do so very slowly compared to humans. They need training samples - and lots of them - to work on a highly integrated training set.

Thats where the problems lie. To make progress, they would need to have human input on a large scale, and they would be constantly behind the times in the lessons they learn. For something equivalent to human intelligence, my guess is that it would take the same basic number of operations - perhaps we could get an order of magnitude more effiency due to not needing self-regulatory parts of the brain, but not much more than that. 

And that amount of computational horsepower is far beyond what is on display here. 

So no, I'm not really seeing it yet, the replacement of knowledge workers.
@Greg Mattson I'm not sure I understand. Can you say a bit more?
I totally agree. It's wrong so much it's annoying. It's still a really cool tool. There's uses for it, but it's not changing anything right now. Maybe in 10-20 years AI will be that good

@Greg Mattson but Greg, you are proving my point. Take your AlphaGo example, assuming you are correct, it would take a human almost 14 years to play 10,000 games. AlphaGo Zero was fully trained in just 40 days and will still absolutely destroy any and all opponents you can find. So much for that human efficiency. And I don't think we need to hypothesize about how good it would it be if it didn't have a tree search, mainly because it does have a tree search.

As for making the corrections you mentioned, the errors definitely won't be addressed on a one-off basis like you talked about. It doesn't work like that at all. The training data will be improved upon in such a way that the hallucinations are minimized to an acceptable level. And specialized purpose-built AI may be able to automate this process all by itself, such that the error correction process of other AI models may conceptually resemble what it looked like to train AlphaGo with millions of Go games.

@Morgan ok put it this way. I didn't realize it when I watched this video, but there is literally no architecture change between chatGPT and GPT-3. In fact, GPT-3 is *smaller*. The only thing that chatGPT has going for it and what makes it so 'revolutionary' is the fact that it was trained with human feedback. So they basically sized down the model and threw people at it. 

Hence the same issues that plague large-scale systems remain - inability to learn on the fly, need for a large sample size to make inferences, lack of internal reflection and reason. This isn't a revolution in structure, its a PR exercise.

Now its impressive I understand, but there is nothing at all like a human's way of learning from small sample sizes. Take go for instance. When alphago is trained on millions of games, without a tree search, it gets to about the same level as a professional human. That same professional human - if they played 2 games a day, would play about 10,000 games to get to the same level. There is therefore an efficiency factor of 1000-10000 or so per example between a human and a a bot. 

So take it to the examples here. To get the equivalent level of accuracy here, they are going to have to train GPT for each use case, each program, show exactly what they did wrong, and do it 10,000 times to train it generically with a given rule.

I don't know - perhaps they could use the internet for this, but its an incredibly resource constrained problem. I suppose you could use git diffs and patches along with the text of their inputs for this, but I just don't see a large corpus of people going through each mistake GPT makes and correcting them. It's very much a constraint to how fast the models can progress.

So again, I'm not really worried here - GPT right now seems to me much like stack overflow only with errors that snuck into the code samples. Try and ask it any business logic related problem for example, and see what you get.

I don't know man, you are taking a very "human" approach here. It may very well take us humans a long time to work through the long tail of that last 10% - but AI is progressing at an exponential rate, where that last 10% may actually be solved in the blink of an eye. And I mean that literally. As for self driving cars, the only people who anticipated it being available already are Elon Musk and his fanboy army. The researchers and engineers who actually do the work are more realistic about such estimates. I write software in Silicon Valley myself and I agree with this guy more than I disagree - the only thing I'd change is to push the time frame out to 10 years instead of 5. The hardware side of the equation I think is a bit further behind, so they may need a bit longer to make datacenters adequately efficient at scale. Who knows, maybe all this never happens, but I think it is more likely than not at this point.

@Nikt Niewiem 
I too have been studying AIs... Since about 1995. I know Eliezer Yudkowsky personally (and we've talked and broken bread together.) And you are absolutely right, diffusion is nothing like neural nets and there are even a number of unique models for neural networks. Recent advances in temporal models are looking particularly fascinating. Producing results that look the most like the kinds of "Thinking Systems" we're most used to. 

Another key difference between biological and synthetic brains at the moment is the storage in biological brains lives in each nerve cell and is accessible at the same time as the processing. If we implemented that in hardware and are able to design a "SLEEP" mode for these models, that would let them pack learning efficiently and store it in long term memory. It would be a profound advance allowing us to teach these networks many different things and have them remember each distinctly.

The point I was making, was that each of these different things represents a model for observed function in biological brains... this piecemeal approach is slowly evolving into a more comprehensive system that will incorporate all these things we see now in a vastly larger and more complex system. The largest synthetic brain today is around 100 million neurons. Three orders of magnitude smaller than ours. We are already seeing the smaller neural networks used in "Language Systems" display spectral responses in their data processing that look virtually identical to the very same networks in human brains. This tells us our models are working in ways virtually identical to the natural systems. A human equivalent synthetic brain, and the artificial consciousness it will contain, are virtually foregone conclusions. In 10 years maybe a couple more, we will see strong AI, unless, our governments and/or scientists decide such a thing is too inherently dangerous, and forbid its creation. Of course business will push hard for it seeing the possibility for profit.

@Met. I'd highly recommend investigating the difference between Private and Personal property. The exchange of goods and resources is not capitalism, that's just a market or an economy. 

Capitalism is a specific system where the means of production are owned as private property which the owners gain profit from by exploiting human labor, without needing to contribute any significant labor themselves. This is the actual system of capitalism and that is the thing that needs to change. Capitalists have worked long and hard to confuse the concept of the exchange of resources as synonymous, but they are not. 

So I'm not saying people will ever stop exchanging goods. I'm saying the specific mechanism for doing so, which we currently use - ie capitalism - isn't laid out in a way which is compatible with AI completely upending how goods and services are produced in a way that so drastically removes human labor from the equation. 

Unfortunately the propaganda meant to confuse the idea of a market or economy with capitalism is definitely going to make having the discussions we're going to have to start having moving forward, more difficult.

@Met. That's the myth they want us to believe, but, Just for shiggles, I asked GPT to elaborate on the contradictions between human nature and capitalism:

There are a number of contradictions between human nature and capitalism, which can be understood as the inherent tension between our natural tendencies and desires as human beings, and the demands and constraints of the capitalist system. Some of these contradictions include:

    The pursuit of individual self-interest versus the need for cooperation and collaboration: In capitalism, individuals are encouraged to pursue their own self-interest and to compete with one another in order to succeed. However, human beings are also naturally inclined to cooperate and work together for the common good, and this can be at odds with the individualistic ethos of capitalism.

    The desire for security and stability versus the forces of competition and change: Capitalism is characterized by constant change and competition, as firms must adapt to changing market conditions and consumers must continually seek out new products and services. This can be at odds with our natural desire for security and stability, as the unpredictable nature of capitalism can create uncertainty and insecurity.

    The drive for personal fulfillment and meaning versus the demands of the market: In capitalism, individuals are often judged by their ability to produce and consume, and their worth is measured by their economic value. This can be at odds with our natural desire for personal fulfillment and meaning, as the pursuit of economic success may not always align with our deeper values and aspirations.

Overall, there are many contradictions between human nature and capitalism, and these can create challenges and conflicts for individuals who are trying to live and thrive within the capitalist system.
